         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Eastereve ¶ 1885. ¶  ¶ I have every reason to think, dear Prof. Tate, that the tall Xanthorrhoea of Kangaroo-Island, is a distinct species. It seems nearer to  ¶ X. australis ¶  than to any of the two...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">85.04.04a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Ralph Tate</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Barr Smith Library, University of Adelaide, SA.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Eastereve</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">1885.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">In 1885, Easter Day was 5 April.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have every reason to think, dear Prof. Tate, that the tall Xanthorrhoea of Kangaroo-Island, is a distinct species. It seems nearer to <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">X. australis</hi>
               </seg> than to any of the two, occurring near St Vincent's Gulf, and as <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">you</hi>
               </seg> were the first, to draw particular attention to it, I have called it X. Tateana, and written an article on the subject, which will soon appear.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B85.07.01.</p>
               </note> It might be well, to mention this at the next meeting of the R. S. of S. Australia. In justice to Mr Tepper I would like to mention, that he thought already the species distinct from X. quadrangulata, and I have now fuller information and material, confirmatory of that view, from Mess Somerville &amp; Wilks, who in a very enterprising manner made the collecting of Xanthorrhoea-resin in various parts of Australia and so also in your colony a matter of mercantile business.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Xanthorrhoea%20australis">Xanthorrhoea australis</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Xanthorrhoea%20quadrangulata">Xanthorrhoea quadrangulata</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Xanthorrhoea%20Tateana">Xanthorrhoea Tateana</name>
            </p>
